    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-08T16:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-08T16:41:00-05:00" n="120"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d120">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3272</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Langhorne</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-08T22:00:00+00:19">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 8, 1917, 10 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 9, 2.45 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>712. My 706 of the 4th.<note n="1" xml:id="d120fn1">Not printed.</note> In a note
                    just received from the Minister of Foreign Affairs he states that <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="flushleft">there is no occasion in this instance for the Government
                            of the Queen to follow the same line of action as the United States, in
                            view of the fact that the attitude of the American Government, contrary
                            to that of the Government of the Queen, logically results from the state
                            of affairs created by the negotiations on this subject which have
                            previously been conducted between the United States and Germany. … that
                            the Government of the Queen has just addressed an energetic protest to
                            the German Government on the subject of the new measure inasmuch as it
                            seriously jeopardizes the principle of the freedom of the high seas as
                            well as the laws of humanity.<note n="2" xml:id="d120fn2">Above text
                                corrected to accord with that later received by pouch (File No
                                763.72/3520).</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Langhorne</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
